content.problemStatement:
**Destructors** are special functions called automatically when an **object is about to be destroyed**. Think of a constructor as the "birth" of an object and a destructor as its "death." A destructor's main job is to release resources acquired during the object's lifetime, It essentially cleans up anything the object "owns" before being destroyed.

**Syntax:**
```cpp
~ClassName() { // the tilde ~ symbol is used to declare a destructor
        // Destructor code here
}
```
---
**Example:**
```cpp
#include 
using namespace std;

class Sample {
public:
    // Constructor
    Sample() {
        cout << "Constructor called!" << endl;
    }

    // Destructor
    ~Sample() {
        cout << "Destructor called: Object is being destroyed!" << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    // Create an object of Sample
    Sample obj;  // Constructor is called here

    // Object goes out of scope at the end of main
    return 0;  // Destructor will be called automatically here
}
```
**Expected Output:**
```default
Constructor called!
Destructor called: Object is being destroyed!
```

